// pancake-os build daemon protocol.        *** PROPOSAL, not wired up ***
//
// pancake-build-server runs centrally on an orchestrator host. It does the
// heavy work that today happens on every client (`pancake bootstrap`
// on the build host, `pancake install`/`pancake update` inside a VM):
//
//   - mmdebstrap / apt-get download
//   - per-package overlay-snapshot + dpkg --unpack/--configure
//   - mkfs.ext4 + veritysetup → image.img + image.hash + roothash
//   - manifest.toml synthesis, signed with one of the daemon's keys
//
// Clients call BuildLayer/LookupLayer/GetLayer over gRPC. The daemon
// caches every built layer on disk forever, keyed by roothash; the
// reverse index from (pkg, version, suite, arch) → roothash is used
// to short-circuit BuildLayer when the result is already known.
//
// The roothash IS the layer's identity. Two BuildLayer calls with the
// same spec MUST return the same roothash (assuming the underlying
// .deb hasn't been re-uploaded upstream). This sidesteps the
// mkfs.ext4-reproducibility problem from the client-side build path
// (existing task #33): there is exactly one build per layer, done by
// the daemon, cached forever — clients never rebuild, they download.
//
// Trust:
//   - Each LayerHandle carries a manifest.toml + manifest.sig where
//     the sig is RSA-PKCS1v15-SHA256 over manifest.toml under one of
//     the daemon's signing keys (selected by signing_key_id).
//   - The roothash inside the manifest.toml is the cryptographic
//     identity of image.img (verity root). Clients re-verify on
//     receipt: bytes are streamed → veritysetup format → compare
//     against manifest.toml's roothash.
//   - This means GetLayer transport can be untrusted (bytes are
//     content-addressed). But BuildLayer/BuildGeneration/UploadBlob
//     are bearer-token authenticated (same systemd-creds sealed
//     pattern as pancaked uses today; see DefaultSealedTokenPath in
//     internal/orchsrv).
//
// Out of scope for this service:
//   - `pancake-host` layer. Per-host by definition; clients build it
//     locally from inputs they shouldn't send to a shared cache.
//     Contents (post-rework):
//       /etc/hostname
//       /etc/machine-id                   (placeholder; systemd
//                                          regenerates at first boot)
//       /etc/ssh/ssh_host_*_key{,.pub}
//       /etc/ssh/sshd_config
//       /root/.ssh/authorized_keys
//       /etc/resolv.conf
//       /etc/systemd/network/10-wired.network
//   - The orchestrator-side "push manifest to a fleet of VMs"
//     workflow lives in the existing orchpb Pancake service.
